Your Honor,

I stand before you today, humbled by the gravity of my actions and with a deep sense of remorse. I am fully aware of the harm I caused and the potential danger I put myself and others in. I accept full responsibility for the offense of careless driving.

On the day in question, I was rushing to the airport to pick up my family members who were arriving. In my haste, I made the ill-advised decision to drive aggressively and at a higher speed than permitted. I also allowed myself to be distracted by a text message from my cousin. These reckless choices led to the unfortunate outcome of crashing into a guardrail.

Fortunately, no one else was injured as a result of my actions, and for this, I am immensely grateful. However, I am aware that this does not diminish the seriousness of the offense. I acknowledge that my prior record already has 3 penalty points for speeding, which reflects a lapse in judgment on my part.

Since the incident, I have had time to reflect on the inherent danger and potential consequences of such irresponsible behavior. I have come to realize the harm that I could have caused not only to myself but also to the innocent individuals sharing the road with me that day. This newfound awareness has compelled me to deeply regret my actions and work towards rectifying them.

In terms of my personal circumstances, I am 37 years old with an otherwise clean record. I have always strived to be a law-abiding citizen and contribute positively to society. I am proud to say that I make regular donations to the British Heart Foundation, demonstrating my commitment to supporting worthy causes and making a difference in the lives of others.

I stand before you today, not to seek leniency, but to acknowledge my wrongdoing and express my genuine remorse. I fully accept the consequences of my actions and I am prepared to face any penalties deemed appropriate by this court.

In conclusion, Your Honor, I plead guilty to the offense of careless driving. I recognize the severity of my actions and the potential harm I could have caused. I humbly request your consideration of the mitigating factors present in my case, including my clean record, my contributions to society, and my genuine remorse. I assure you that I have learned from this experience and will take the necessary steps to ensure that I never commit a similar offense again.

Thank you for your time and attention.

Sincerely,

Charlotte Porter

